            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How this priming sugar calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This priming sugar calculator estimates how much fermentable
                sugar you need to add at bottling to reach a target carbonation
                level (in volumes of CO₂) for your beer style, taking into
                account:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>Beer volume (liters or US gallons)</li>
                <li>
                  Beer temperature (°C or °F) and its residual dissolved CO₂
                </li>
                <li>Target carbonation level in volumes of CO₂</li>
                <li>Priming sugar type and its effective fermentability</li>
                <li>Bottle size, to show per-bottle sugar amounts</li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Carbonation and residual CO₂</h3>
              <p>
                Finished beer already contains some dissolved CO₂ from
                fermentation. Colder beer holds more CO₂, so you need less
                priming sugar. Warmer beer holds less CO₂ and needs more sugar
                to reach the same carbonation.
              </p>
              <p>
                This tool uses a standard empirical model to estimate residual
                CO₂ as a function of beer temperature:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="mb-1 font-mono">
                  CO₂<sub>residual</sub> (vol) ≈ 3.0378 − 0.050062 × T +
                  0.00026555 × T²
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600">
                  where T is beer temperature in °C.
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>The amount of CO₂ that must be produced by priming is:</p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-mono">
                  CO₂<sub>to produce</sub> = CO₂<sub>target</sub> − CO₂<sub
                    >residual</sub
                  >
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>From CO₂ volumes to grams of sugar</h3>
              <p>
                For fully fermentable dry sugars (like dextrose or sucrose), a
                practical brewing approximation is:
              </p>
              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-mono mb-1">
                  grams of sugar = k × V × (CO₂<sub>target</sub> −
                  CO₂<sub>residual</sub>)
                </p>
                <p class="text-xs text-gray-600">
                  where V is beer volume in liters and k is a sugar-specific
                  constant (around 4.0–4.2 for corn sugar).
                </p>
              </div>
              <p>
                Less fermentable priming sources (like DME or honey) require
                more weight to produce the same CO₂. The calculator applies a
                fermentability factor for each sugar type and lets you define a
                custom factor for other fermentables.
              </p>

              <h3>Supported priming sugar types</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Corn sugar (dextrose):</strong> very common, neutral
                  flavor, highly fermentable.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Table sugar (sucrose):</strong> also common; slightly
                  more fermentable than dextrose by weight.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Dry malt extract (DME):</strong> less fermentable and
                  contains unfermentable solids; requires more grams.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Honey:</strong> contains water and variable
                  fermentability; this tool uses a typical average factor.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Custom fermentable:</strong> specify your own
                  effective fermentability factor if you have lab data or a
                  trusted reference.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Typical carbonation ranges by beer style</h3>
              <div class="table-scroll">
                <table class="min-w-full text-sm border border-gray-200">
