              <h2>Step-by-step: how to prime your beer safely</h2>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  <strong>Confirm fermentation is complete.</strong> Take stable
                  gravity readings over at least 2–3 days.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Measure beer volume and temperature.</strong> Use the
                  true volume in the bottling bucket and the highest temperature
                  reached after fermentation.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Choose your target carbonation.</strong> Use the style
                  presets or set a custom CO₂ level.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Select sugar type.</strong> Pick corn sugar, table
                  sugar, DME, honey, or a custom fermentable.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Use the calculator.</strong> Enter your values and
                  note the total grams of sugar required.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Prepare a priming solution.</strong> Boil the sugar in
                  a small amount of water (e.g., 1–2 cups / 250–500 mL), cool to
                  room temperature.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Gently mix with beer.</strong> Add the cooled solution
                  to the bottling bucket and gently stir to distribute without
                  splashing.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Bottle and condition.</strong> Fill bottles, cap, and
                  store at 18–22 °C (64–72 °F) for 1–3 weeks before chilling and
                  serving.
                </li>
              </ol>

              <h2>Safety tips and common pitfalls</h2>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Always <strong>measure sugar by weight</strong>, not by cups
                  or spoons.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Do not “round up” sugar amounts; it is safer to be slightly
                  under-carbonated than to risk bottle bombs.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use bottles rated for the carbonation level (e.g., champagne
                  bottles for very high carbonation).
                </li>
                <li>
                  Avoid adding priming sugar directly to individual bottles
                  unless you are very consistent and use a dosing tool.
                </li>
                <li>
                  If you are unsure about your beer’s fermentation status, wait
                  longer or re-check gravity before bottling.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h2>FAQ</h2>

              <h3>How much priming sugar do I need per liter or gallon?</h3>
              <p>
                For a typical ale at 2.3–2.5 volumes of CO₂, you will often end
                up around <strong>5–7 g of corn sugar per liter</strong>, or
                about <strong>0.7–1 oz per US gallon</strong>. The exact amount
                depends on beer temperature, target CO₂, and sugar type, so
                always rely on the calculator instead of fixed rules of thumb.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I mix different priming sugars?</h3>
              <p>
                Yes, but it complicates the math. If you mix sugars, you can
                either:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Use the calculator separately for each sugar portion and add
                  the results, or
                </li>
                <li>
                  Approximate a combined fermentability factor and use the
                  custom fermentable option.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>
                What if my beer fermented at a different temperature than
                bottling?
              </h3>
              <p>
                Use the <strong>warmest temperature</strong> the beer reached
                after active fermentation. That is when most CO₂ escaped and
                determines the residual CO₂ level. If you cold-crash after that,
                the residual CO₂ does not increase significantly.
              </p>

              <h3>Can I use this calculator for kegging?</h3>
              <p>
                This tool is optimized for bottle conditioning. For kegs, you
                usually force-carbonate using pressure and temperature charts
                rather than priming sugar. However, some brewers do prime kegs;
                in that case, you can still use this calculator with the keg
                volume.
              </p>
